            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "David Tanaka\u2019s name often prompts a question, one he\u2019s happy to answer. Born David Miller in suburban Ohio, his early life was shaped by his mother, a fiercely independent nurse. His world expanded when she married Kenji Tanaka, a kind, brilliant Japanese-American civil engineer who adopted David at age ten. From Kenji, David learned not just about Japanese culture, but about the elegant logic of systems\u2014how bridges, roads, and infrastructure formed the invisible skeleton of society. This became the blueprint for his life\u2019s purpose.\n\nAfter earning a political science degree from Ohio State, David followed his burgeoning passion for civic infrastructure to UC Berkeley, where he completed a Master's in Public Policy. His early career saw him managing transit logistics in smaller California cities, learning the nuts and bolts of public service away from the intense spotlight of a major metropolis. The call from the SFMTA felt like a summons to the major leagues. He was drawn to the beautiful, maddening beast of San Francisco's transit system, a challenge he has now wrestled with for eighteen years.\n\nNow Deputy Director, David\u2019s life is inextricably linked to the city's pulse. He lives in a neatly kept one-bedroom apartment in Duboce Triangle, chosen for its direct access to the N Judah line. His 3.5-mile commute is his daily focus group; he feels every jerky stop and unexpected delay alongside the public he serves. The long hours and immense stress of his job contributed to an amicable divorce a decade ago; his adult daughter now works as a graphic designer in Portland.\n\nHis social life is small but steady, consisting of a weekly trivia night with other civic employees and a weekend hiking group. David\u2019s dream isn\u2019t a promotion, but a legacy of function. He yearns to see one of his major projects\u2014like a truly efficient bus rapid transit on a key corridor\u2014fully realized and embraced. He fantasizes about retiring to a quieter coastal town, but his profound sense of responsibility keeps him tethered to the city, riding the rails each morning, notepad in hand, forever trying to make the system just a little bit better."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.  He was ten, sitting at the kitchen table. Kenji had laid out a brush, an inkstone, and paper. He didn't just tell David his new name; he showed him how to draw the characters for Tanaka: \u7530\u4e2d, \"rice field\" and \"center.\" As David copied the strokes, a quiet, profound sense of belonging settled in his chest. It wasn\u2019t just a new name; it was a new map for his life, one built on intention and structure. This was the first system Kenji ever taught him.\n\n2.  Kenji took him to see a bridge being retrofitted when he was thirteen. Standing on the overlook, David felt the hum of machinery through his sneakers. Kenji didn\u2019t point at the cranes; he pointed at the steel rebar inside the concrete, explaining how tension and compression held thousands of lives aloft every day. \u201cIt\u2019s the skeleton, Davey,\u201d he\u2019d said. \u201cPeople only notice when it breaks.\u201d In that moment, David decided he wanted to be a person who noticed *before* it broke.\n\n3.  His first week at the SFMTA, eighteen years ago. He rode the N Judah from his new apartment, not as a commuter, but as a custodian. The jerky lurch out of the Sunset Tunnel, the sudden burst of light, and the city sprawling below\u2014it felt like a contract. The weight of every delayed passenger and broken-down streetcar landed squarely on his shoulders. He felt a terrifying, exhilarating sense of purpose. He was finally in the major leagues.\n\n4.  His daughter, Maya, was nine and had the lead in her school play. That same night, a water main break flooded the Castro station, shutting down the entire Muni Metro. He remembers standing in the damp, chaotic station, his phone buzzing with texts from his then-wife, while he coordinated bus shuttles. He missed the play. That night solidified the personal toll of public service\u2014a trade-off that cemented his path and contributed to the eventual, amicable unraveling of his marriage.\n\n5.  About five years ago, after months of modeling and meetings, they implemented his signal timing plan along the 38 Geary line. The first morning it went live, he stood at Masonic Avenue, just watching. He saw three buses in a row sail through the intersection. No one else noticed. No one applauded. But for David, seeing that elegant, invisible system function perfectly was a feeling purer than any promotion. It was a glimpse of the quiet, working legacy he craved."
